            <div class="prose max-w-none" x-show="lang === 'en'" x-cloak>
                <h2>Section 1: Pre-Audit Preparation</h2>
<p>Before initiating the compliance audit, operations staff need to complete the following preparations:</p>
<h3>1.1 Define Audit Scope</h3>
<ul>
<li>List of advertising accounts to be audited this time</li>
<li>Audit time period (recommended to cover the last 30 days)</li>
<li>Key platforms to focus on: Meta (Facebook/Instagram), Google Ads, TikTok Ads, etc.</li>
</ul>
<h3>1.2 Prepare Audit Tools</h3>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Tool Type</th>
<th>Purpose</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Account Dashboard</td>
<td>Check account status, balance, and spending details</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Policy Center</td>
<td>Review the latest advertising policies on each platform</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Creative Review Tools</td>
<td>Detect violations in images and text</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Audit Log Sheet</td>
<td>Record issues found and remediation status</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Recommendation</strong>: Establish a shared document template and fill it in directly during each audit to improve efficiency.</p>
</blockquote>
<h2>Section 2: Conducting the Audit</h2>
<h3>Step 1: Account Status Verification</h3>
<ol>
<li>Log into the ad dashboard and check for the following anomalies:</li>
<li>Account suspended or restricted</li>
<li>Payment method failed or declined</li>
<li>
<p>Abnormal balance reduction (possible erroneous charges or fraudulent clicks)</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Cross-reference with account opening information to confirm account entity, business license, and backend information are consistent</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Check for any unresolved policy warning emails</p>
</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Common Issue</strong>: A cross-border e-commerce team once had their account temporarily restricted due to an expired business license. It is recommended to set a reminder 30 days before document expiration.</p>
</blockquote>
<h3>Step 2: Advertising Policy Compliance Check</h3>
<p>Verify ad settings against target market regulations:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Target Audience Age</strong>: Does it comply with local minimum advertising age restrictions (e.g., some regions require 16+ under GDPR)</li>
<li><strong>Sensitive Categories</strong>: Do finance, healthcare, and gambling ads have corresponding qualification certificates</li>
<li><strong>Data Collection Statement</strong>: Does the landing page include Cookie consent or privacy policy links</li>
<li><strong>Intellectual Property</strong>: Do ad copy and images involve brand or celebrity authorization</li>
</ul>
<h3>Step 3: Creative Compliance Spot Check</h3>
<p>Randomly review 20% of running creatives monthly:</p>
<ul>
<li>Images: Any excessive exposure, violent elements, or misleading comparison images</li>
<li>Text: Any absolute terms (like "best" or "100% effective") or false promises</li>
<li>CTA Buttons: Consistent with landing page content, avoiding exaggerated claims</li>
</ul>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Practical Tip</strong>: Use platform-native creative diagnostic tools (like Meta Creative Hub) to preview creative compliance and identify potential issues in advance.</p>
</blockquote>
<h3>Step 4: Spending and Reconciliation Check</h3>
<ul>
<li>Verify that backend spending reports match financial reconciliation statements</li>
<li>Investigate abnormal clicks or invalid traffic (can be identified through platform-native data reports)</li>
<li>Check for any unauthorized ad spending (such as account compromise)</li>
</ul>
<h2>Section 3: Issue Handling</h2>
<p>Issues found during audits are categorized into three severity levels:</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Level</th>
<th>Manifestation</th>
<th>Response Deadline</th>
<th>Actions</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>P0</td>
<td>Account banned or serious violation</td>
<td>Within 24 hours</td>
<td>Submit appeal materials, pause related campaigns</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>P1</td>
<td>Violation risk but no penalty triggered</td>
<td>Within 3 days</td>
<td>Modify creatives or adjust audience settings</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>P2</td>
<td>Minor optimization suggestions</td>
<td>Within 7 days</td>
<td>Document and schedule optimization</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<h2>Section 4: Audit Schedule and Record Archiving</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Daily Audit</strong>: Account balance alerts, abnormal spending notifications</li>
<li><strong>Weekly Audit</strong>: Creative compliance spot checks, policy update notifications</li>
<li><strong>Monthly Audit</strong>: Comprehensive compliance audit, issue review and summary</li>
</ul>
<p>After each audit, complete the audit log sheet with: audit date, person responsible, issues found, remediation measures, and remediation results, to form a closed loop.</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Conclusion</strong>: Compliance auditing is not a one-time task but a continuous effort integrated into daily operations. It is recommended that teams print and post the SOP in visible areas of the workspace and use it as training material for new employee onboarding, reducing account risks caused by operational oversight.</p>
